interventions.DESCRIPTION / IMPLEMENTATION STRATEGY::
The demonstrated tendency for people to be overly optimistic about the outcome of planned actions. This includes over-estimating the likelihood of positive events and under-estimating the likelihood of negative events.

Armor and Taylor review a number of studies that have found optimism bias in different kinds of judgment. These include:

  - Second-year MBA students overestimated the number of job offers they would receive and their starting salary;
  - Students overestimated the scores they would achieve on exams;
  - Almost all newlyweds in a US study expected their marriage to last a lifetime, even while aware of divorce statistics;
  - Professional financial analysts consistently overestimated corporate earnings;
  - Most smokers believe they are less at risk of developing smoking-related diseases than others who smoke.

Companies have exploited this bias by increasing interest rates to punitive rates for any late payment, knowing that overconfidence causes many people to grossly underestimate their odds of making a payment late.
Optimism bias could be an important factor to keep in mind, both for the person changing their behavior, and anyone supporting them in doing so, at every stage of behavior change (from the planning through to implementation and maintenance of the behavior). It has been documented to be a persistent tendency in healthy adults (ref), and it has the potential to either be helpful or counterproductive to behavior change, depending on how unrealistic it is and depending on what the optimism pertains to. For example, the tendency to persist in the face of challenges (which could be seen as a form of behavioral optimism) appears to be predicted by a person's level of intellectual humility ([Porter et al., 2020](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1041608020300686?casa_token=sJNl4ThLbWUAAAAA:E8U8KRkr11qvyWjYzRoIIiR8SaC_J2L9rML1N-a1qBt0CgNVIEPjWli410B7hb0ONUG7HtQ8x-8)). If intellectual humility is a quality that can be nurtured or encouraged, then this might represent an attractive way to encourage people to persist in the face of challenges (behavioral optimism), without encouraging them to become overconfident. Optimism bias can also interact with the Observer-expectancy Effect and the placebo effect. As long as the person being encouraged is aware of the biased nature of this reasoning (and is therefore not being misled as to the intentions behind such encouragement), and as long as the person's expectations are not so high as to be unrealistic, having optimistic expectations in and of themselves could increase the probability that the person performs better than they would have (had their expectations been lower). For example, if you think that there is a 75% probability that three months from now, your friend will be engaging in moderate-intensity physical activity for between 20 and 150 minutes per week, and their goal is to do that for at least 120 minutes per week,  reminding them that they *can* do it would be both true and encouraging, and may help them to feel more optimistic about their chances of success (compared to e.g. reminding them that there's also a decent chance that they could fall well short of their goal). However, it is also worth keeping in mind that encouragement is only one factor that could influence the degree of optimism bias someone experiences; it may also be driven by their own personal characteristics and health conditions, including whether they have depression (which has been documented to decrease or even reverse this bias, to the detriment of the person's wellbeing [todo: ref]). There are also cases were optimism bias could be excessive, to the point of causing the person to form unrealistic ideas about their abilities or about the best ways of implementing and continuing the behavior; in such cases, a benevolent helper could help the person to adjust their beliefs, by clearly explaining the actual probability of success in engaging in behavior change in similar scenarios, and by helping people to think about the probabilities of negative outcomes, and plans for responding to them.

